south of Stirling, Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Langton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Langton, Berwickshire, Scotland","scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Veteri","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Alfonse, Carmine, Luigi, Nino, Salvator, Salvatore.","Italian (southern): nickname from Latin <i>vetus</i>, <i>veteris</i> ‘old, aged’ or, in some instances, from a short form of a habitational name from Castelevetere (Avellino and Benevento province) or Santa Maria Capua Vetere (in Caserta province)."],"variants":[{"name":"Vetrone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Fernando, Rito.","Italian: from an augmentative of   Vetere  ."]},{"name":"Vetro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Rocco, Angelo, Antonio, Armonda, Vincenzo.","Italian (southern, mainly Sicily):","variant of   Vetere  ."]}]},{"name":"Ponte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jorge, Carlos, Enrique, Fernando, Graciela, Mario, Miguel, Alberto, Alejandro, Alicia.  Portuguese Albano, Joao.  Italian Antonio, Alessandra, Angelo, Cesare, Dino, Elio, Enrico, Ettore, Luigi, Salvatore.","Italian, Galician, and Portuguese: topographic name for someone who lived near a bridge, <i>ponte</i>, or a habitational name from any of numerous places in Italy, Galicia, and Portugal named with this word. Compare   Da Ponte  .","English (Hampshire): variant of   Pont  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Da Ponte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Mario, Alvardo, Americo, Christiano, Diego, Fernando, Francisco, Hermano, Humberto.  Portuguese Joao, Albano.  Italian Aniello, Antonino, Antonio, Giuseppe, Lorenzo, Marino, Quido.","Italian and Portuguese; Galician (mainly <b>Daponte</b>): variant of   Ponte  , with the addition of preposition <i>da</i> ‘from the’."]},{"name":"Ponti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Ivano, Octavio, Dulce, Elena, Elida, Franca, Marco, Primo, Raffaele, Silvio.","Italian:","patronymic or plural form of   Ponte  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Veteri Ponte was born as the son of William de Veteri-Ponte of Langton, Carriden & Bolton and Petronilla de Veteri Ponte. He had at least 1 daughter with Anina. He died on 24 June 1314, in Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–23 or 24 June 1314, die